It&#8217;s alleged that a secret group of law enforcement officials would regularly to discuss bringing criminal charges against Pravin Gordhan. JOHANNESBURG - Civil society organisation Freedom Under Law is asking National Prosecuting Authority (NPA) head Shaun Abrahams to explain his alleged involvement in a secret group of law enforcement officials who regularly met to discuss the charging of Finance Minister Pravin Gordhan. The explosive claim is included in the organisation s urgent court application to try and get the president to suspend Abrahams and prosecutors Sibongile Mzinyathi and Torie Pretorius. In its urgent court application, Freedom Under Law says it understands that Abrahams was at all relevant times a member of the so-called 'reference group'. This group allegedly included government officials, and or intelligence officials, police officials and law enforcement personnel. It alleges that they would regularly and secretly meet at the NPA offices to discuss criminal investigations and the bringing of criminal charges against Gordhan and former Sars commissioners Ivan Pillay and Oupa Magashula. The organisation has invited Abrahams to explain these interactions and his involvement in the group. The NDPP has repeatedly stated he was not acting in the interests of any political powers when charging Gordhan and he is not politically captured.MUST WATCH: Shaun Abrahams on political capture, charging a president and more